{"formatVersion":"1","manifest":{"sourceId":"khayyamRubaiyat","displayName":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam","type":"quotes","language":"English","edition":"Edward FitzGerald 5th Edition, 1889","primaryCategory":"Poetry & Literature","subcategory":"Poetry","audienceTags":["literature","poetry"],"sortPriority":53,"itemCount":213,"supportsRandom":true,"supportsBrowse":true,"browseOrder":"sequence","groupingLevels":["stanza"],"groupingLabels":["Stanza"],"dataPath":"Data/Collections/Khayyam_Rubaiyat.json","version":"1.0"},"data":[{"id":"rubaiyat-1","text":"Introduction.\nFirst Edition.\nFifth Edition.\nNotes.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 1 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"1"},"sequenceIndex":0},{"id":"rubaiyat-2","text":"\"At Naishapur thus lived and died Omar Khayyam, 'busied,' adds the\nVizier, 'in winning knowledge of every kind, and especially in\nAstronomy, wherein he attained to a very high pre-eminence.  Under the\nSultanate of Malik Shah, he came to Merv, and obtained great praise\nfor his proficiency in science, and the Sultan showered favors upon\nhim.'","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 2 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"2"},"sequenceIndex":1},{"id":"rubaiyat-3","text":"\"His Takhallus or poetical name (Khayyam) signifies a Tent-maker, and\nhe is said to have at one time exercised that trade, perhaps before\nNizam-ul-Mulk's generosity raised him to independence.  Many Persian\npoets similarly derive their names from their occupations; thus we\nhave Attar, 'a druggist,' Assar, 'an oil presser,' etc.[2]  Omar\nhimself alludes to his name in the following whimsical lines:--","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 3 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"3"},"sequenceIndex":2},{"id":"rubaiyat-4","text":"\"'Khayyam, who stitched the tents of science,\nHas fallen in grief's furnace and been suddenly burned;\nThe shears of Fate have cut the tent ropes of his life,\nAnd the broker of Hope has sold him for nothing!'","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 4 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"4"},"sequenceIndex":3},{"id":"rubaiyat-5","text":"\"We have only one more anecdote to give of his Life, and that relates\nto the close; it is told in the anonymous preface which is sometimes\nprefixed to his poems; it has been printed in the Persian in the\nAppendix to Hyde's Veterum Persarum Religio, p. 499; and D'Herbelot\nalludes to it in his Bibliotheque, under Khiam.[3]--","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 5 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"5"},"sequenceIndex":4},{"id":"rubaiyat-6","text":"Thus far--without fear of Trespass--from the Calcutta Review.  The\nwriter of it, on reading in India this story of Omar's Grave, was\nreminded, he says, of Cicero's Account of finding Archimedes' Tomb at\nSyracuse, buried in grass and weeds.  I think Thorwaldsen desired to\nhave roses grow over him; a wish religiously fulfilled for him to the\npresent day, I believe.  However, to return to Omar.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 6 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"6"},"sequenceIndex":5},{"id":"rubaiyat-7","text":"\"O Thou who burn'st in Heart for those who burn\nIn Hell, whose fires thyself shall feed in turn,\nHow long be crying, 'Mercy on them, God!'\nWhy, who art Thou to teach, and He to learn?\"","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 7 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"7"},"sequenceIndex":6},{"id":"rubaiyat-8","text":"\"If I myself upon a looser Creed\nHave loosely strung the Jewel of Good deed,\nLet this one thing for my Atonement plead:\nThat One for Two I never did misread.\"","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 8 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"8"},"sequenceIndex":7},{"id":"rubaiyat-9","text":"While the second Edition of this version of Omar was preparing,\nMonsieur Nicolas, French Consul at Resht, published a very careful and\nvery good Edition of the Text, from a lithograph copy at Teheran,\ncomprising 464 Rubaiyat, with translation and notes of his own.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 9 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"9"},"sequenceIndex":8},{"id":"rubaiyat-10","text":"Mons. Nicolas, whose Edition has reminded me of several things, and\ninstructed me in others, does not consider Omar to be the material\nEpicurean that I have literally taken him for, but a Mystic, shadowing\nthe Deity under the figure of Wine, Wine-bearer, &c., as Hafiz is\nsupposed to do; in short, a Sufi Poet like Hafiz and the rest.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 10 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"10"},"sequenceIndex":9},{"id":"rubaiyat-11","text":"[Footnote 1: Some of Omar's Rubaiyat warn us of the danger of Greatness, the\ninstability of Fortune, and while advocating Charity to all Men,\nrecommending us to be too intimate with none.  Attar makes Nizam-ul-Mulk\nuse the very words of his friend Omar [Rub. xxviii.], \"When Nizam-ul-\nMulk was in the Agony (of Death) he said, 'Oh God!  I am passing away in\nthe hand of the wind.'\"]","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 11 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"11"},"sequenceIndex":10},{"id":"rubaiyat-12","text":"[Footnote 3: \"Philosophe Musulman qui a vecu en Odeur de Saintete dans sa\nReligion, vers la Fin du premier et le Commencement du second Siecle,\"\nno part of which, except the \"Philosophe,\" can apply to our Khayyam.]","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 12 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"12"},"sequenceIndex":11},{"id":"rubaiyat-13","text":"[Footnote 5: \"Since this paper was written\" (adds the Reviewer in a note), \"we\nhave met with a Copy of a very rare Edition, printed at Calcutta in\n1836.  This contains 438 Tetrastichs, with an Appendix containing 54\nothers not found in some MSS.\"]","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 13 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"13"},"sequenceIndex":12},{"id":"rubaiyat-14","text":"[Footnote 7:  Perhaps would have edited the Poems himself some years ago.  He may\nnow as little approve of my Version on one side, as of Mons. Nicolas'\nTheory on the other.]","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 14 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"14"},"sequenceIndex":13},{"id":"rubaiyat-15","text":"Awake! for Morning in the Bowl of Night\nHas flung the Stone that puts the Stars to Flight:\nAnd Lo! the Hunter of the East has caught\nThe Sultan's Turret in a Noose of Light.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 15 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"15"},"sequenceIndex":14},{"id":"rubaiyat-16","text":"Dreaming when Dawn's Left Hand was in the Sky\nI heard a Voice within the Tavern cry,\n\"Awake, my Little ones, and fill the Cup\nBefore Life's Liquor in its Cup be dry.\"","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 16 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"16"},"sequenceIndex":15},{"id":"rubaiyat-17","text":"And, as the Cock crew, those who stood before\nThe Tavern shouted--\"Open then the Door.\nYou know how little while we have to stay,\nAnd, once departed, may return no more.\"","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 17 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"17"},"sequenceIndex":16},{"id":"rubaiyat-18","text":"Now the New Year reviving old Desires,\nThe thoughtful Soul to Solitude retires,\nWhere the WHITE HAND OF MOSES on the Bough\nPuts out, and Jesus from the Ground suspires.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 18 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"18"},"sequenceIndex":17},{"id":"rubaiyat-19","text":"Iram indeed is gone with all its Rose,\nAnd Jamshyd's Sev'n-ring'd Cup where no one knows;\nBut still the Vine her ancient Ruby yields,\nAnd still a Garden by the Water blows.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 19 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"19"},"sequenceIndex":18},{"id":"rubaiyat-20","text":"And David's Lips are lock't; but in divine\nHigh piping Pelevi, with \"Wine!  Wine!  Wine!\nRed Wine!\"--the Nightingale cries to the Rose\nThat yellow Cheek of hers to'incarnadine.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 20 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"20"},"sequenceIndex":19},{"id":"rubaiyat-21","text":"Come, fill the Cup, and in the Fire of Spring\nThe Winter Garment of Repentance fling:\nThe Bird of Time has but a little way\nTo fly--and Lo! the Bird is on the Wing.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 21 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"21"},"sequenceIndex":20},{"id":"rubaiyat-22","text":"And look--a thousand Blossoms with the Day\nWoke--and a thousand scatter'd into Clay:\nAnd this first Summer Month that brings the Rose\nShall take Jamshyd and Kaikobad away.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 22 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"22"},"sequenceIndex":21},{"id":"rubaiyat-23","text":"But come with old Khayyam, and leave the Lot\nOf Kaikobad and Kaikhosru forgot:\nLet Rustum lay about him as he will,\nOr Hatim Tai cry Supper--heed them not.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 23 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"23"},"sequenceIndex":22},{"id":"rubaiyat-24","text":"With me along some Strip of Herbage strown\nThat just divides the desert from the sown,\nWhere name of Slave and Sultan scarce is known,\nAnd pity Sultan Mahmud on his Throne.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 24 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"24"},"sequenceIndex":23},{"id":"rubaiyat-25","text":"Here with a Loaf of Bread beneath the Bough,\nA Flask of Wine, a Book of Verse--and Thou\nBeside me singing in the Wilderness--\nAnd Wilderness is Paradise enow.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 25 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"25"},"sequenceIndex":24},{"id":"rubaiyat-26","text":"\"How sweet is mortal Sovranty!\"--think some:\nOthers--\"How blest the Paradise to come!\"\nAh, take the Cash in hand and waive the Rest;\nOh, the brave Music of a distant Drum!","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 26 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"26"},"sequenceIndex":25},{"id":"rubaiyat-27","text":"Look to the Rose that blows about us--\"Lo,\nLaughing,\" she says, \"into the World I blow:\nAt once the silken Tassel of my Purse\nTear, and its Treasure on the Garden throw.\"","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 27 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"27"},"sequenceIndex":26},{"id":"rubaiyat-28","text":"The Worldly Hope men set their Hearts upon\nTurns Ashes--or it prospers; and anon,\nLike Snow upon the Desert's dusty Face\nLighting a little Hour or two--is gone.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 28 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"28"},"sequenceIndex":27},{"id":"rubaiyat-29","text":"And those who husbanded the Golden Grain,\nAnd those who flung it to the Winds like Rain,\nAlike to no such aureate Earth are turn'd\nAs, buried once, Men want dug up again.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 29 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"29"},"sequenceIndex":28},{"id":"rubaiyat-30","text":"Think, in this batter'd Caravanserai\nWhose Doorways are alternate Night and Day,\nHow Sultan after Sultan with his Pomp\nAbode his Hour or two, and went his way.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 30 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"30"},"sequenceIndex":29},{"id":"rubaiyat-31","text":"They say the Lion and the Lizard keep\nThe Courts where Jamshyd gloried and drank deep:\nAnd Bahram, that great Hunter--the Wild Ass\nStamps o'er his Head, and he lies fast asleep.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 31 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"31"},"sequenceIndex":30},{"id":"rubaiyat-32","text":"I sometimes think that never blows so red\nThe Rose as where some buried Caesar bled;\nThat every Hyacinth the Garden wears\nDropt in its Lap from some once lovely Head.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 32 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"32"},"sequenceIndex":31},{"id":"rubaiyat-33","text":"And this delightful Herb whose tender Green\nFledges the River's Lip on which we lean--\nAh, lean upon it lightly! for who knows\nFrom what once lovely Lip it springs unseen!","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 33 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"33"},"sequenceIndex":32},{"id":"rubaiyat-34","text":"Ah! my Beloved, fill the Cup that clears\nTO-DAY of past Regrets and future Fears-\nTo-morrow?--Why, To-morrow I may be\nMyself with Yesterday's Sev'n Thousand Years.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 34 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"34"},"sequenceIndex":33},{"id":"rubaiyat-35","text":"Lo! some we loved, the loveliest and the best\nThat Time and Fate of all their Vintage prest,\nHave drunk their Cup a Round or two before,\nAnd one by one crept silently to Rest.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 35 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"35"},"sequenceIndex":34},{"id":"rubaiyat-36","text":"And we, that now make merry in the Room\nThey left, and Summer dresses in new Bloom,\nOurselves must we beneath the Couch of Earth\nDescend, ourselves to make a Couch--for whom?","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 36 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"36"},"sequenceIndex":35},{"id":"rubaiyat-37","text":"Ah, make the most of what we yet may spend,\nBefore we too into the Dust Descend;\nDust into Dust, and under Dust, to lie,\nSans Wine, sans Song, sans Singer and--sans End!","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 37 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"37"},"sequenceIndex":36},{"id":"rubaiyat-38","text":"Alike for those who for TO-DAY prepare,\nAnd those that after a TO-MORROW stare,\nA Muezzin from the Tower of Darkness cries\n\"Fools! your Reward is neither Here nor There.\"","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 38 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"38"},"sequenceIndex":37},{"id":"rubaiyat-39","text":"Why, all the Saints and Sages who discuss'd\nOf the Two Worlds so learnedly, are thrust\nLike foolish Prophets forth; their Words to Scorn\nAre scatter'd, and their Mouths are stopt with Dust.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 39 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"39"},"sequenceIndex":38},{"id":"rubaiyat-40","text":"Oh, come with old Khayyam, and leave the Wise\nTo talk; one thing is certain, that Life flies;\nOne thing is certain, and the Rest is Lies;\nThe Flower that once has blown for ever dies.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 40 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"40"},"sequenceIndex":39},{"id":"rubaiyat-41","text":"Myself when young did eagerly frequent\nDoctor and Saint, and heard great Argument\nAbout it and about: but evermore\nCame out by the same Door as in I went.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 41 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"41"},"sequenceIndex":40},{"id":"rubaiyat-42","text":"With them the Seed of Wisdom did I sow,\nAnd with my own hand labour'd it to grow:\nAnd this was all the Harvest that I reap'd--\n\"I came like Water, and like Wind I go.\"","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 42 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"42"},"sequenceIndex":41},{"id":"rubaiyat-43","text":"Into this Universe, and why not knowing,\nNor whence, like Water willy-nilly flowing:\nAnd out of it, as Wind along the Waste,\nI know not whither, willy-nilly blowing.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 43 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"43"},"sequenceIndex":42},{"id":"rubaiyat-44","text":"What, without asking, hither hurried whence?\nAnd, without asking, whither hurried hence!\nAnother and another Cup to drown\nThe Memory of this Impertinence!","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 44 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"44"},"sequenceIndex":43},{"id":"rubaiyat-45","text":"Up from Earth's Centre through the seventh Gate\nI rose, and on the Throne of Saturn sate,\nAnd many Knots unravel'd by the Road;\nBut not the Knot of Human Death and Fate.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 45 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"45"},"sequenceIndex":44},{"id":"rubaiyat-46","text":"There was a Door to which I found no Key:\nThere was a Veil past which I could not see:\nSome little Talk awhile of ME and THEE\nThere seemed--and then no more of THEE and ME.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 46 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"46"},"sequenceIndex":45},{"id":"rubaiyat-47","text":"Then to the rolling Heav'n itself I cried,\nAsking, \"What Lamp had Destiny to guide\nHer little Children stumbling in the Dark?\"\nAnd--\"A blind understanding!\" Heav'n replied.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 47 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"47"},"sequenceIndex":46},{"id":"rubaiyat-48","text":"Then to this earthen Bowl did I adjourn\nMy Lip the secret Well of Life to learn:\nAnd Lip to Lip it murmur'd--\"While you live,\nDrink!--for once dead you never shall return.\"","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 48 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"48"},"sequenceIndex":47},{"id":"rubaiyat-49","text":"I think the Vessel, that with fugitive\nArticulation answer'd, once did live,\nAnd merry-make; and the cold Lip I kiss'd\nHow many Kisses might it take--and give.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 49 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"49"},"sequenceIndex":48},{"id":"rubaiyat-50","text":"For in the Market-place, one Dusk of Day,\nI watch'd the Potter thumping his wet Clay:\nAnd with its all obliterated Tongue\nIt murmur'd--\"Gently, Brother, gently, pray!\"","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 50 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"50"},"sequenceIndex":49},{"id":"rubaiyat-51","text":"Ah, fill the Cup:--what boots it to repeat\nHow Time is slipping underneath our Feet:\nUnborn TO-MORROW and dead YESTERDAY,\nWhy fret about them if TO-DAY be sweet!","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 51 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"51"},"sequenceIndex":50},{"id":"rubaiyat-52","text":"One Moment in Annihilation's Waste,\nOne moment, of the Well of Life to taste--\nThe Stars are setting, and the Caravan\nStarts for the dawn of Nothing--Oh, make haste!","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 52 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"52"},"sequenceIndex":51},{"id":"rubaiyat-53","text":"How long, how long, in infinite Pursuit\nOf This and That endeavour and dispute?\nBetter be merry with the fruitful Grape\nThan sadden after none, or bitter, Fruit.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 53 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"53"},"sequenceIndex":52},{"id":"rubaiyat-54","text":"You know, my Friends, how long since in my House\nFor a new Marriage I did make Carouse:\nDivorced old barren Reason from my Bed,\nAnd took the Daughter of the Vine to Spouse.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 54 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"54"},"sequenceIndex":53},{"id":"rubaiyat-55","text":"For \"IS\" and \"IS-NOT\" though with Rule and Line,\nAnd, \"UP-AND-DOWN\" without, I could define,\nI yet in all I only cared to know,\nWas never deep in anything but--Wine.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 55 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"55"},"sequenceIndex":54},{"id":"rubaiyat-56","text":"And lately, by the Tavern Door agape,\nCame stealing through the Dusk an Angel Shape,\nBearing a vessel on his Shoulder; and\nHe bid me taste of it; and 'twas--the Grape!","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 56 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"56"},"sequenceIndex":55},{"id":"rubaiyat-57","text":"The Grape that can with Logic absolute\nThe Two-and-Seventy jarring Sects confute:\nThe subtle Alchemist that in a Trice\nLife's leaden Metal into Gold transmute.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 57 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"57"},"sequenceIndex":56},{"id":"rubaiyat-58","text":"The mighty Mahmud, the victorious Lord,\nThat all the misbelieving and black Horde\nOf Fears and Sorrows that infest the Soul\nScatters and slays with his enchanted Sword.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 58 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"58"},"sequenceIndex":57},{"id":"rubaiyat-59","text":"But leave the Wise to wrangle, and with me\nThe Quarrel of the Universe let be:\nAnd, in some corner of the Hubbub coucht,\nMake Game of that which makes as much of Thee.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 59 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"59"},"sequenceIndex":58},{"id":"rubaiyat-60","text":"For in and out, above, about, below,\n'Tis nothing but a Magic Shadow-show,\nPlay'd in a Box whose Candle is the Sun,\nRound which we Phantom Figures come and go.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 60 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"60"},"sequenceIndex":59},{"id":"rubaiyat-61","text":"And if the Wine you drink, the Lip you press,\nEnd in the Nothing all Things end in--Yes-\nThen fancy while Thou art, Thou art but what\nThou shalt be--Nothing--Thou shalt not be less.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 61 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"61"},"sequenceIndex":60},{"id":"rubaiyat-62","text":"While the Rose blows along the River Brink,\nWith old Khayyam the Ruby Vintage drink:\nAnd when the Angel with his darker Draught\nDraws up to thee--take that, and do not shrink.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 62 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"62"},"sequenceIndex":61},{"id":"rubaiyat-63","text":"'Tis all a Chequer-board of Nights and Days\nWhere Destiny with Men for Pieces plays:\nHither and thither moves, and mates, and slays,\nAnd one by one back in the Closet lays.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 63 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"63"},"sequenceIndex":62},{"id":"rubaiyat-64","text":"The Ball no Question makes of Ayes and Noes,\nBut Right or Left as strikes the Player goes;\nAnd He that toss'd Thee down into the Field,\nHe knows about it all--HE knows--HE knows!","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 64 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"64"},"sequenceIndex":63},{"id":"rubaiyat-65","text":"The Moving Finger writes; and, having writ,\nMoves on: nor all thy Piety nor Wit\nShall lure it back to cancel half a Line,\nNor all thy Tears wash out a Word of it.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 65 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"65"},"sequenceIndex":64},{"id":"rubaiyat-66","text":"And that inverted Bowl we call The Sky,\nWhereunder crawling coop't we live and die,\nLift not thy hands to IT for help--for It\nRolls impotently on as Thou or I.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 66 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"66"},"sequenceIndex":65},{"id":"rubaiyat-67","text":"With Earth's first Clay They did the Last Man's knead,\nAnd then of the Last Harvest sow'd the Seed:\nYea, the first Morning of Creation wrote\nWhat the Last Dawn of Reckoning shall read.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 67 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"67"},"sequenceIndex":66},{"id":"rubaiyat-68","text":"I tell Thee this--When, starting from the Goal,\nOver the shoulders of the flaming Foal\nOf Heav'n Parwin and Mushtari they flung,\nIn my predestin'd Plot of Dust and Soul","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 68 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"68"},"sequenceIndex":67},{"id":"rubaiyat-69","text":"The Vine had struck a Fibre; which about\nIf clings my Being--let the Sufi flout;\nOf my Base Metal may be filed a Key,\nThat shall unlock the Door he howls without.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 69 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"69"},"sequenceIndex":68},{"id":"rubaiyat-70","text":"And this I know: whether the one True Light,\nKindle to Love, or Wrath consume me quite,\nOne Glimpse of It within the Tavern caught\nBetter than in the Temple lost outright.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 70 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"70"},"sequenceIndex":69},{"id":"rubaiyat-71","text":"Oh Thou who didst with Pitfall and with Gin\nBeset the Road I was to wander in,\nThou wilt not with Predestination round\nEnmesh me, and impute my Fall to Sin?","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 71 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"71"},"sequenceIndex":70},{"id":"rubaiyat-72","text":"Oh Thou, who Man of baser Earth didst make,\nAnd who with Eden didst devise the Snake;\nFor all the Sin wherewith the Face of Man\nIs blacken'd, Man's Forgiveness give--and take!","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 72 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"72"},"sequenceIndex":71},{"id":"rubaiyat-73","text":"Listen again.  One Evening at the Close\nOf Ramazan, ere the better Moon arose,\nIn that old Potter's Shop I stood alone\nWith the clay Population round in Rows.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 73 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"73"},"sequenceIndex":72},{"id":"rubaiyat-74","text":"And strange to tell, among that Earthen Lot\nSome could articulate, while others not:\nAnd suddenly one more impatient cried--\n\"Who is the Potter, pray, and who the Pot?\"","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 74 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"74"},"sequenceIndex":73},{"id":"rubaiyat-75","text":"Then said another--\"Surely not in vain\nMy substance from the common Earth was ta'en,\nThat He who subtly wrought me into Shape\nShould stamp me back to common Earth again.\"","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 75 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"75"},"sequenceIndex":74},{"id":"rubaiyat-76","text":"Another said--\"Why, ne'er a peevish Boy\nWould break the Bowl from which he drank in Joy;\nShall He that made the Vessel in pure Love\nAnd Fansy, in an after Rage destroy!\"","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 76 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"76"},"sequenceIndex":75},{"id":"rubaiyat-77","text":"None answer'd this; but after Silence spake\nA Vessel of a more ungainly Make:\n\"They sneer at me for leaning all awry;\nWhat? did the Hand then of the Potter shake?\"","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 77 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"77"},"sequenceIndex":76},{"id":"rubaiyat-78","text":"Said one--\"Folks of a surly Tapster tell,\nAnd daub his Visage with the Smoke of Hell;\nThey talk of some strict Testing of us--Pish!\nHe's a Good Fellow, and 'twill all be well.\"","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 78 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"78"},"sequenceIndex":77},{"id":"rubaiyat-79","text":"Then said another with a long-drawn Sigh,\n\"My Clay with long oblivion is gone dry:\nBut, fill me with the old familiar Juice,\nMethinks I might recover by-and-bye!\"","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 79 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"79"},"sequenceIndex":78},{"id":"rubaiyat-80","text":"So, while the Vessels one by one were speaking,\nOne spied the little Crescent all were seeking:\nAnd then they jogg'd each other, \"Brother! Brother!\nHark to the Porter's Shoulder-knot a-creaking!\"","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 80 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"80"},"sequenceIndex":79},{"id":"rubaiyat-81","text":"Ah, with the Grape my fading Life provide,\nAnd wash my Body whence the life has died,\nAnd in a Windingsheet of Vineleaf wrapt,\nSo bury me by some sweet Gardenside.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 81 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"81"},"sequenceIndex":80},{"id":"rubaiyat-82","text":"That ev'n my buried Ashes such a Snare\nOf Perfume shall fling up into the Air,\nAs not a True Believer passing by\nBut shall be overtaken unaware.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 82 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"82"},"sequenceIndex":81},{"id":"rubaiyat-83","text":"Indeed, the Idols I have loved so long\nHave done my Credit in Men's Eye much wrong:\nHave drown'd my Honour in a shallow Cup,\nAnd sold my Reputation for a Song.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 83 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"83"},"sequenceIndex":82},{"id":"rubaiyat-84","text":"Indeed, indeed, Repentance oft before\nI swore--but was I sober when I swore?\nAnd then and then came Spring, and Rose-in-hand\nMy thread-bare Penitence a-pieces tore.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 84 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"84"},"sequenceIndex":83},{"id":"rubaiyat-85","text":"And much as Wine has play'd the Infidel,\nAnd robb'd me of my Robe of Honour--well,\nI often wonder what the Vintners buy\nOne half so precious as the Goods they sell.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 85 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"85"},"sequenceIndex":84},{"id":"rubaiyat-86","text":"Alas, that Spring should vanish with the Rose!\nThat Youth's sweet-scented Manuscript should close!\nThe Nightingale that in the Branches sang,\nAh, whence, and whither flown again, who knows!","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 86 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"86"},"sequenceIndex":85},{"id":"rubaiyat-87","text":"Ah, Love! could thou and I with Fate conspire\nTo grasp this sorry Scheme of Things entire,\nWould not we shatter it to bits--and then\nRe-mould it nearer to the Heart's Desire!","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 87 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"87"},"sequenceIndex":86},{"id":"rubaiyat-88","text":"Ah, Moon of my Delight who know'st no wane,\nThe Moon of Heav'n is rising once again:\nHow oft hereafter rising shall she look\nThrough this same Garden after me--in vain!","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 88 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"88"},"sequenceIndex":87},{"id":"rubaiyat-89","text":"And when Thyself with shining Foot shall pass\nAmong the Guests Star-scatter'd on The Grass,\nAnd in Thy joyous Errand reach the Spot\nWhere I made one--turn down an empty Glass!","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 89 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"89"},"sequenceIndex":88},{"id":"rubaiyat-90","text":"WAKE! For the Sun, who scatter'd into flight\nThe Stars before him from the Field of Night,\nDrives Night along with them from Heav'n, and strikes\nThe Sultan's Turret with a Shaft of Light.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 90 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"90"},"sequenceIndex":89},{"id":"rubaiyat-91","text":"Before the phantom of False morning died,\nMethought a Voice within the Tavern cried,\n\"When all the Temple is prepared within,\n\"Why nods the drowsy Worshiper outside?\"","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 91 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"91"},"sequenceIndex":90},{"id":"rubaiyat-92","text":"And, as the Cock crew, those who stood before\nThe Tavern shouted--\"Open then the Door!\n\"You know how little while we have to stay,\nAnd, once departed, may return no more.\"","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 92 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"92"},"sequenceIndex":91},{"id":"rubaiyat-93","text":"Now the New Year reviving old Desires,\nThe thoughtful Soul to Solitude retires,\nWhere the WHITE HAND OF MOSES on the Bough\nPuts out, and Jesus from the Ground suspires.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 93 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"93"},"sequenceIndex":92},{"id":"rubaiyat-94","text":"Iram indeed is gone with all his Rose,\nAnd Jamshyd's Sev'n-ring'd Cup where no one knows;\nBut still a Ruby kindles in the Vine,\nAnd many a Garden by the Water blows.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 94 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"94"},"sequenceIndex":93},{"id":"rubaiyat-95","text":"And David's lips are lockt; but in divine\nHigh-piping Pehlevi, with \"Wine! Wine! Wine!\n\"Red Wine!\"--the Nightingale cries to the Rose\nThat sallow cheek of hers to' incarnadine.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 95 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"95"},"sequenceIndex":94},{"id":"rubaiyat-96","text":"Come, fill the Cup, and in the fire of Spring\nYour Winter garment of Repentance fling:\nThe Bird of Time has but a little way\nTo flutter--and the Bird is on the Wing.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 96 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"96"},"sequenceIndex":95},{"id":"rubaiyat-97","text":"Whether at Naishapur or Babylon,\nWhether the Cup with sweet or bitter run,\nThe Wine of Life keeps oozing drop by drop,\nThe Leaves of Life keep falling one by one.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 97 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"97"},"sequenceIndex":96},{"id":"rubaiyat-98","text":"Each Morn a thousand Roses brings, you say:\nYes, but where leaves the Rose of Yesterday?\nAnd this first Summer month that brings the Rose\nShall take Jamshyd and Kaikobad away.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 98 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"98"},"sequenceIndex":97},{"id":"rubaiyat-99","text":"Well, let it take them!  What have we to do\nWith Kaikobad the Great, or Kaikhosru?\nLet Zal and Rustum bluster as they will,\nOr Hatim call to Supper--heed not you.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 99 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"99"},"sequenceIndex":98},{"id":"rubaiyat-100","text":"With me along the strip of Herbage strown\nThat just divides the desert from the sown,\nWhere name of Slave and Sultan is forgot--\nAnd Peace to Mahmud on his golden Throne!","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 100 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"100"},"sequenceIndex":99},{"id":"rubaiyat-101","text":"A Book of Verses underneath the Bough,\nA Jug of Wine, a Loaf of Bread--and Thou\nBeside me singing in the Wilderness--\nOh, Wilderness were Paradise enow!","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 101 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"101"},"sequenceIndex":100},{"id":"rubaiyat-102","text":"Some for the Glories of This World; and some\nSigh for the Prophet's Paradise to come;\nAh, take the Cash, and let the Credit go,\nNor heed the rumble of a distant Drum!","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 102 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"102"},"sequenceIndex":101},{"id":"rubaiyat-103","text":"Look to the blowing Rose about us--\"Lo,\nLaughing,\" she says, \"into the world I blow,\nAt once the silken tassel of my Purse\nTear, and its Treasure on the Garden throw.\"","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 103 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"103"},"sequenceIndex":102},{"id":"rubaiyat-104","text":"And those who husbanded the Golden grain,\nAnd those who flung it to the winds like Rain,\nAlike to no such aureate Earth are turn'd\nAs, buried once, Men want dug up again.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 104 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"104"},"sequenceIndex":103},{"id":"rubaiyat-105","text":"The Worldly Hope men set their Hearts upon\nTurns Ashes--or it prospers; and anon,\nLike Snow upon the Desert's dusty Face,\nLighting a little hour or two--is gone.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 105 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"105"},"sequenceIndex":104},{"id":"rubaiyat-106","text":"Think, in this batter'd Caravanserai\nWhose Portals are alternate Night and Day,\nHow Sultan after Sultan with his Pomp\nAbode his destined Hour, and went his way.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 106 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"106"},"sequenceIndex":105},{"id":"rubaiyat-107","text":"They say the Lion and the Lizard keep\nThe courts where Jamshyd gloried and drank deep:\nAnd Bahram, that great Hunter--the Wild Ass\nStamps o'er his Head, but cannot break his Sleep.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 107 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"107"},"sequenceIndex":106},{"id":"rubaiyat-108","text":"I sometimes think that never blows so red\nThe Rose as where some buried Caesar bled;\nThat every Hyacinth the Garden wears\nDropt in her Lap from some once lovely Head.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 108 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"108"},"sequenceIndex":107},{"id":"rubaiyat-109","text":"And this reviving Herb whose tender Green\nFledges the River-Lip on which we lean--\nAh, lean upon it lightly! for who knows\nFrom what once lovely Lip it springs unseen!","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 109 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"109"},"sequenceIndex":108},{"id":"rubaiyat-110","text":"Ah, my Beloved, fill the Cup that clears\nTO-DAY of past Regrets and future Fears:\nTo-morrow--Why, To-morrow I may be\nMyself with Yesterday's Sev'n thousand Years.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 110 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"110"},"sequenceIndex":109},{"id":"rubaiyat-111","text":"For some we loved, the loveliest and the best\nThat from his Vintage rolling Time hath prest,\nHave drunk their Cup a Round or two before,\nAnd one by one crept silently to rest.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 111 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"111"},"sequenceIndex":110},{"id":"rubaiyat-112","text":"And we, that now make merry in the Room\nThey left, and Summer dresses in new bloom,\nOurselves must we beneath the Couch of Earth\nDescend--ourselves to make a Couch--for whom?","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 112 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"112"},"sequenceIndex":111},{"id":"rubaiyat-113","text":"Ah, make the most of what we yet may spend,\nBefore we too into the Dust descend;\nDust into Dust, and under Dust to lie,\nSans Wine, sans Song, sans Singer, and--sans End!","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 113 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"113"},"sequenceIndex":112},{"id":"rubaiyat-114","text":"Alike for those who for TO-DAY prepare,\nAnd those that after some TO-MORROW stare,\nA Muezzin from the Tower of Darkness cries,\n\"Fools! your Reward is neither Here nor There.\"","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 114 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"114"},"sequenceIndex":113},{"id":"rubaiyat-115","text":"Why, all the Saints and Sages who discuss'd\nOf the Two Worlds so wisely--they are thrust\nLike foolish Prophets forth; their Words to Scorn\nAre scatter'd, and their Mouths are stopt with Dust.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 115 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"115"},"sequenceIndex":114},{"id":"rubaiyat-116","text":"Myself when young did eagerly frequent\nDoctor and Saint, and heard great argument\nAbout it and about: but evermore\nCame out by the same door where in I went.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 116 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"116"},"sequenceIndex":115},{"id":"rubaiyat-117","text":"With them the seed of Wisdom did I sow,\nAnd with mine own hand wrought to make it grow;\nAnd this was all the Harvest that I reap'd--\n\"I came like Water, and like Wind I go.\"","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 117 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"117"},"sequenceIndex":116},{"id":"rubaiyat-118","text":"Into this Universe, and Why not knowing\nNor Whence, like Water willy-nilly flowing;\nAnd out of it, as Wind along the Waste,\nI know not Whither, willy-nilly blowing.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 118 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"118"},"sequenceIndex":117},{"id":"rubaiyat-119","text":"What, without asking, hither hurried Whence?\nAnd, without asking, Whither hurried hence!\nOh, many a Cup of this forbidden Wine\nMust drown the memory of that insolence!","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 119 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"119"},"sequenceIndex":118},{"id":"rubaiyat-120","text":"Up from Earth's Center through the Seventh Gate\nI rose, and on the Throne of Saturn sate,\nAnd many a Knot unravel'd by the Road;\nBut not the Master-knot of Human Fate.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 120 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"120"},"sequenceIndex":119},{"id":"rubaiyat-121","text":"There was the Door to which I found no Key;\nThere was the Veil through which I might not see:\nSome little talk awhile of ME and THEE\nThere was--and then no more of THEE and ME.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 121 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"121"},"sequenceIndex":120},{"id":"rubaiyat-122","text":"Earth could not answer; nor the Seas that mourn\nIn flowing Purple, of their Lord Forlorn;\nNor rolling Heaven, with all his Signs reveal'd\nAnd hidden by the sleeve of Night and Morn.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 122 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"122"},"sequenceIndex":121},{"id":"rubaiyat-123","text":"Then of the THEE IN ME who works behind\nThe Veil, I lifted up my hands to find\nA lamp amid the Darkness; and I heard,\nAs from Without--\"THE ME WITHIN THEE BLIND!\"","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 123 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"123"},"sequenceIndex":122},{"id":"rubaiyat-124","text":"Then to the Lip of this poor earthen Urn\nI lean'd, the Secret of my Life to learn:\nAnd Lip to Lip it murmur'd--\"While you live,\n\"Drink!--for, once dead, you never shall return.\"","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 124 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"124"},"sequenceIndex":123},{"id":"rubaiyat-125","text":"I think the Vessel, that with fugitive\nArticulation answer'd, once did live,\nAnd drink; and Ah! the passive Lip I kiss'd,\nHow many Kisses might it take--and give!","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 125 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"125"},"sequenceIndex":124},{"id":"rubaiyat-126","text":"For I remember stopping by the way\nTo watch a Potter thumping his wet Clay:\nAnd with its all-obliterated Tongue\nIt murmur'd--\"Gently, Brother, gently, pray!\"","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 126 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"126"},"sequenceIndex":125},{"id":"rubaiyat-127","text":"And has not such a Story from of Old\nDown Man's successive generations roll'd\nOf such a clod of saturated Earth\nCast by the Maker into Human mold?","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 127 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"127"},"sequenceIndex":126},{"id":"rubaiyat-128","text":"And not a drop that from our Cups we throw\nFor Earth to drink of, but may steal below\nTo quench the fire of Anguish in some Eye\nThere hidden--far beneath, and long ago.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 128 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"128"},"sequenceIndex":127},{"id":"rubaiyat-129","text":"As then the Tulip for her morning sup\nOf Heav'nly Vintage from the soil looks up,\nDo you devoutly do the like, till Heav'n\nTo Earth invert you--like an empty Cup.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 129 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"129"},"sequenceIndex":128},{"id":"rubaiyat-130","text":"Perplext no more with Human or Divine,\nTo-morrow's tangle to the winds resign,\nAnd lose your fingers in the tresses of\nThe Cypress-slender Minister of Wine.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 130 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"130"},"sequenceIndex":129},{"id":"rubaiyat-131","text":"And if the Wine you drink, the Lip you press,\nEnd in what All begins and ends in--Yes;\nThink then you are TO-DAY what YESTERDAY\nYou were--TO-MORROW you shall not be less.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 131 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"131"},"sequenceIndex":130},{"id":"rubaiyat-132","text":"So when that Angel of the darker Drink\nAt last shall find you by the river-brink,\nAnd, offering his Cup, invite your Soul\nForth to your Lips to quaff--you shall not shrink.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 132 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"132"},"sequenceIndex":131},{"id":"rubaiyat-133","text":"Why, if the Soul can fling the Dust aside,\nAnd naked on the Air of Heaven ride,\nWere't not a Shame--were't not a Shame for him\nIn this clay carcass crippled to abide?","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 133 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"133"},"sequenceIndex":132},{"id":"rubaiyat-134","text":"'Tis but a Tent where takes his one day's rest\nA Sultan to the realm of Death addrest;\nThe Sultan rises, and the dark Ferrash\nStrikes, and prepares it for another Guest.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 134 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"134"},"sequenceIndex":133},{"id":"rubaiyat-135","text":"And fear not lest Existence closing your\nAccount, and mine, should know the like no more;\nThe Eternal Saki from that Bowl has pour'd\nMillions of Bubbles like us, and will pour.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 135 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"135"},"sequenceIndex":134},{"id":"rubaiyat-136","text":"When You and I behind the Veil are past,\nOh, but the long, long while the World shall last,\nWhich of our Coming and Departure heeds\nAs the Sea's self should heed a pebble-cast.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 136 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"136"},"sequenceIndex":135},{"id":"rubaiyat-137","text":"A Moment's Halt--a momentary taste\nOf BEING from the Well amid the Waste--\nAnd Lo!--the phantom Caravan has reach'd\nThe NOTHING it set out from--Oh, make haste!","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 137 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"137"},"sequenceIndex":136},{"id":"rubaiyat-138","text":"Would you that spangle of Existence spend\nAbout THE SECRET--quick about it, Friend!\nA Hair perhaps divides the False from True--\nAnd upon what, prithee, may life depend?","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 138 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"138"},"sequenceIndex":137},{"id":"rubaiyat-139","text":"A Hair perhaps divides the False and True;\nYes; and a single Alif were the clue--\nCould you but find it--to the Treasure-house,\nAnd peradventure to THE MASTER too;","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 139 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"139"},"sequenceIndex":138},{"id":"rubaiyat-140","text":"Whose secret Presence through Creation's veins\nRunning Quicksilver-like eludes your pains;\nTaking all shapes from Mah to Mahi and\nThey change and perish all--but He remains;","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 140 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"140"},"sequenceIndex":139},{"id":"rubaiyat-141","text":"A moment guessed--then back behind the Fold\nImmerst of Darkness round the Drama roll'd\nWhich, for the Pastime of Eternity,\nHe doth Himself contrive, enact, behold.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 141 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"141"},"sequenceIndex":140},{"id":"rubaiyat-142","text":"But if in vain, down on the stubborn floor\nOf Earth, and up to Heav'n's unopening Door,\nYou gaze TO-DAY, while You are You--how then\nTO-MORROW, when You shall be You no more?","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 142 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"142"},"sequenceIndex":141},{"id":"rubaiyat-143","text":"Waste not your Hour, nor in the vain pursuit\nOf This and That endeavor and dispute;\nBetter be jocund with the fruitful Grape\nThan sadden after none, or bitter, Fruit.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 143 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"143"},"sequenceIndex":142},{"id":"rubaiyat-144","text":"You know, my Friends, with what a brave Carouse\nI made a Second Marriage in my house;\nDivorced old barren Reason from my Bed,\nAnd took the Daughter of the Vine to Spouse.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 144 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"144"},"sequenceIndex":143},{"id":"rubaiyat-145","text":"For \"Is\" and \"Is-not\" though with Rule and Line\nAnd \"UP-AND-DOWN\" by Logic I define,\nOf all that one should care to fathom, I\nwas never deep in anything but--Wine.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 145 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"145"},"sequenceIndex":144},{"id":"rubaiyat-146","text":"Ah, by my Computations, People say,\nReduce the Year to better reckoning?--Nay,\n'Twas only striking from the Calendar\nUnborn To-morrow and dead Yesterday.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 146 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"146"},"sequenceIndex":145},{"id":"rubaiyat-147","text":"And lately, by the Tavern Door agape,\nCame shining through the Dusk an Angel Shape\nBearing a Vessel on his Shoulder; and\nHe bid me taste of it; and 'twas--the Grape!","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 147 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"147"},"sequenceIndex":146},{"id":"rubaiyat-148","text":"The Grape that can with Logic absolute\nThe Two-and-Seventy jarring Sects confute:\nThe sovereign Alchemist that in a trice\nLife's leaden metal into Gold transmute;","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 148 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"148"},"sequenceIndex":147},{"id":"rubaiyat-149","text":"The mighty Mahmud, Allah-breathing Lord,\nThat all the misbelieving and black Horde\nOf Fears and Sorrows that infest the Soul\nScatters before him with his whirlwind Sword.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 149 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"149"},"sequenceIndex":148},{"id":"rubaiyat-150","text":"Why, be this Juice the growth of God, who dare\nBlaspheme the twisted tendril as a Snare?\nA Blessing, we should use it, should we not?\nAnd if a Curse--why, then, Who set it there?","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 150 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"150"},"sequenceIndex":149},{"id":"rubaiyat-151","text":"I must abjure the Balm of Life, I must,\nScared by some After-reckoning ta'en on trust,\nOr lured with Hope of some Diviner Drink,\nTo fill the Cup--when crumbled into Dust!","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 151 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"151"},"sequenceIndex":150},{"id":"rubaiyat-152","text":"Of threats of Hell and Hopes of Paradise!\nOne thing at least is certain--This Life flies;\nOne thing is certain and the rest is Lies;\nThe Flower that once has blown for ever dies.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 152 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"152"},"sequenceIndex":151},{"id":"rubaiyat-153","text":"Strange, is it not? that of the myriads who\nBefore us pass'd the door of Darkness through,\nNot one returns to tell us of the Road,\nWhich to discover we must travel too.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 153 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"153"},"sequenceIndex":152},{"id":"rubaiyat-154","text":"The Revelations of Devout and Learn'd\nWho rose before us, and as Prophets burn'd,\nAre all but Stories, which, awoke from Sleep\nThey told their comrades, and to Sleep return'd.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 154 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"154"},"sequenceIndex":153},{"id":"rubaiyat-155","text":"I sent my Soul through the Invisible,\nSome letter of that After-life to spell:\nAnd by and by my Soul return'd to me,\nAnd answer'd \"I Myself am Heav'n and Hell:\"","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 155 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"155"},"sequenceIndex":154},{"id":"rubaiyat-156","text":"Heav'n but the Vision of fulfill'd Desire,\nAnd Hell the Shadow from a Soul on fire,\nCast on the Darkness into which Ourselves,\nSo late emerged from, shall so soon expire.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 156 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"156"},"sequenceIndex":155},{"id":"rubaiyat-157","text":"We are no other than a moving row\nOf Magic Shadow-shapes that come and go\nRound with the Sun-illumined Lantern held\nIn Midnight by the Master of the Show;","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 157 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"157"},"sequenceIndex":156},{"id":"rubaiyat-158","text":"But helpless Pieces of the Game He plays\nUpon this Chequer-board of Nights and Days;\nHither and thither moves, and checks, and slays,\nAnd one by one back in the Closet lays.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 158 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"158"},"sequenceIndex":157},{"id":"rubaiyat-159","text":"The Ball no question makes of Ayes and Noes,\nBut Here or There as strikes the Player goes;\nAnd He that toss'd you down into the Field,\nHe knows about it all--HE knows--HE knows!","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 159 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"159"},"sequenceIndex":158},{"id":"rubaiyat-160","text":"The Moving Finger writes; and, having writ,\nMoves on: nor all your Piety nor Wit\nShall lure it back to cancel half a Line,\nNor all your Tears wash out a Word of it.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 160 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"160"},"sequenceIndex":159},{"id":"rubaiyat-161","text":"And that inverted Bowl they call the Sky,\nWhereunder crawling coop'd we live and die,\nLift not your hands to It for help--for It\nAs impotently moves as you or I.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 161 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"161"},"sequenceIndex":160},{"id":"rubaiyat-162","text":"With Earth's first Clay They did the Last Man knead,\nAnd there of the Last Harvest sow'd the Seed:\nAnd the first Morning of Creation wrote\nWhat the Last Dawn of Reckoning shall read.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 162 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"162"},"sequenceIndex":161},{"id":"rubaiyat-163","text":"YESTERDAY This Day's Madness did prepare;\nTO-MORROW's Silence, Triumph, or Despair:\nDrink! for you not know whence you came, nor why:\nDrink! for you know not why you go, nor where.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 163 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"163"},"sequenceIndex":162},{"id":"rubaiyat-164","text":"I tell you this--When, started from the Goal,\nOver the flaming shoulders of the Foal\nOf Heav'n Parwin and Mushtari they flung,\nIn my predestined Plot of Dust and Soul.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 164 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"164"},"sequenceIndex":163},{"id":"rubaiyat-165","text":"The Vine had struck a fiber: which about\nIf clings my Being--let the Dervish flout;\nOf my Base metal may be filed a Key\nThat shall unlock the Door he howls without.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 165 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"165"},"sequenceIndex":164},{"id":"rubaiyat-166","text":"And this I know: whether the one True Light\nKindle to Love, or Wrath consume me quite,\nOne Flash of It within the Tavern caught\nBetter than in the Temple lost outright.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 166 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"166"},"sequenceIndex":165},{"id":"rubaiyat-167","text":"What! out of senseless Nothing to provoke\nA conscious Something to resent the yoke\nOf unpermitted Pleasure, under pain\nOf Everlasting Penalties, if broke!","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 167 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"167"},"sequenceIndex":166},{"id":"rubaiyat-168","text":"What! from his helpless Creature be repaid\nPure Gold for what he lent him dross-allay'd--\nSue for a Debt he never did contract,\nAnd cannot answer--Oh the sorry trade!","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 168 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"168"},"sequenceIndex":167},{"id":"rubaiyat-169","text":"Oh Thou, who didst with pitfall and with gin\nBeset the Road I was to wander in,\nThou wilt not with Predestined Evil round\nEnmesh, and then impute my Fall to Sin!","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 169 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"169"},"sequenceIndex":168},{"id":"rubaiyat-170","text":"Oh Thou, who Man of baser Earth didst make,\nAnd ev'n with Paradise devise the Snake:\nFor all the Sin wherewith the Face of Man\nIs blacken'd--Man's forgiveness give--and take!","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 170 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"170"},"sequenceIndex":169},{"id":"rubaiyat-171","text":"As under cover of departing Day\nSlunk hunger-stricken Ramazan away,\nOnce more within the Potter's house alone\nI stood, surrounded by the Shapes of Clay.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 171 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"171"},"sequenceIndex":170},{"id":"rubaiyat-172","text":"Shapes of all Sorts and Sizes, great and small,\nThat stood along the floor and by the wall;\nAnd some loquacious Vessels were; and some\nListen'd perhaps, but never talk'd at all.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 172 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"172"},"sequenceIndex":171},{"id":"rubaiyat-173","text":"Said one among them--\"Surely not in vain\nMy substance of the common Earth was ta'en\nAnd to this Figure molded, to be broke,\nOr trampled back to shapeless Earth again.\"","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 173 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"173"},"sequenceIndex":172},{"id":"rubaiyat-174","text":"Then said a Second--\"Ne'er a peevish Boy\nWould break the Bowl from which he drank in joy;\nAnd He that with his hand the Vessel made\nWill surely not in after Wrath destroy.\"","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 174 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"174"},"sequenceIndex":173},{"id":"rubaiyat-175","text":"After a momentary silence spake\nSome Vessel of a more ungainly Make;\n\"They sneer at me for leaning all awry:\nWhat! did the Hand then of the Potter shake?\"","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 175 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"175"},"sequenceIndex":174},{"id":"rubaiyat-176","text":"Whereat some one of the loquacious Lot--\nI think a Sufi pipkin--waxing hot--\n\"All this of Pot and Potter--Tell me then,\nWho is the Potter, pray, and who the Pot?\"","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 176 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"176"},"sequenceIndex":175},{"id":"rubaiyat-177","text":"\"Why,\" said another, \"Some there are who tell\nOf one who threatens he will toss to Hell\nThe luckless Pots he marr'd in making--Pish!\nHe's a Good Fellow, and 'twill all be well.\"","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 177 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"177"},"sequenceIndex":176},{"id":"rubaiyat-178","text":"\"Well,\" murmured one, \"Let whoso make or buy,\nMy Clay with long Oblivion is gone dry:\nBut fill me with the old familiar Juice,\nMethinks I might recover by and by.\"","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 178 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"178"},"sequenceIndex":177},{"id":"rubaiyat-179","text":"So while the Vessels one by one were speaking,\nThe little Moon look'd in that all were seeking:\nAnd then they jogg'd each other, \"Brother! Brother!\nNow for the Porter's shoulders' knot a-creaking!\"","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 179 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"179"},"sequenceIndex":178},{"id":"rubaiyat-180","text":"Ah, with the Grape my fading life provide,\nAnd wash the Body whence the Life has died,\nAnd lay me, shrouded in the living Leaf,\nBy some not unfrequented Garden-side.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 180 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"180"},"sequenceIndex":179},{"id":"rubaiyat-181","text":"That ev'n buried Ashes such a snare\nOf Vintage shall fling up into the Air\nAs not a True-believer passing by\nBut shall be overtaken unaware.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 181 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"181"},"sequenceIndex":180},{"id":"rubaiyat-182","text":"Indeed the Idols I have loved so long\nHave done my credit in this World much wrong:\nHave drown'd my Glory in a shallow Cup,\nAnd sold my reputation for a Song.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 182 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"182"},"sequenceIndex":181},{"id":"rubaiyat-183","text":"Indeed, indeed, Repentance oft before\nI swore--but was I sober when I swore?\nAnd then and then came Spring, and Rose-in-hand\nMy thread-bare Penitence apieces tore.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 183 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"183"},"sequenceIndex":182},{"id":"rubaiyat-184","text":"And much as Wine has play'd the Infidel,\nAnd robb'd me of my Robe of Honor--Well,\nI wonder often what the Vintners buy\nOne half so precious as the stuff they sell.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 184 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"184"},"sequenceIndex":183},{"id":"rubaiyat-185","text":"Yet Ah, that Spring should vanish with the Rose!\nThat Youth's sweet-scented manuscript should close!\nThe Nightingale that in the branches sang,\nAh whence, and whither flown again, who knows!","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 185 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"185"},"sequenceIndex":184},{"id":"rubaiyat-186","text":"Would but the Desert of the Fountain yield\nOne glimpse--if dimly, yet indeed, reveal'd,\nTo which the fainting Traveler might spring,\nAs springs the trampled herbage of the field!","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 186 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"186"},"sequenceIndex":185},{"id":"rubaiyat-187","text":"Would but some winged Angel ere too late\nArrest the yet unfolded Roll of Fate,\nAnd make the stern Recorder otherwise\nEnregister, or quite obliterate!","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 187 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"187"},"sequenceIndex":186},{"id":"rubaiyat-188","text":"Ah Love! could you and I with Him conspire\nTo grasp this sorry Scheme of Things entire,\nWould not we shatter it to bits--and then\nRe-mold it nearer to the Heart's Desire!","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 188 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"188"},"sequenceIndex":187},{"id":"rubaiyat-189","text":"Yon rising Moon that looks for us again--\nHow oft hereafter will she wax and wane;\nHow oft hereafter rising look for us\nThrough this same Garden--and for one in vain!","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 189 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"189"},"sequenceIndex":188},{"id":"rubaiyat-190","text":"And when like her, oh Saki, you shall pass\nAmong the Guests Star-scatter'd on the Grass,\nAnd in your joyous errand reach the spot\nWhere I made One--turn down an empty Glass!","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 190 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"190"},"sequenceIndex":189},{"id":"rubaiyat-191","text":"(II.) The \"False Dawn\"; Subhi Kazib, a transient Light on the Horizon\nabout an hour before the Subhi sadik or True Dawn; a well-known\nPhenomenon in the East.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 191 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"191"},"sequenceIndex":190},{"id":"rubaiyat-192","text":"(IV.) New Year.  Beginning with the Vernal Equinox, it must be\nremembered; and (howsoever the old Solar Year is practically\nsuperseded by the clumsy Lunar Year that dates from the Mohammedan\nHijra) still commemorated by a Festival that is said to have been\nappointed by the very Jamshyd whom Omar so often talks of, and whose\nyearly Calendar he helped to rectify.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 192 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"192"},"sequenceIndex":191},{"id":"rubaiyat-193","text":"'And on old Hyems' Chin and icy Crown\nAn odorous Chaplet of sweet Summer buds\nIs, as in mockery, set--'--","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 193 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"193"},"sequenceIndex":192},{"id":"rubaiyat-194","text":"\"The White Hand of Moses.\"  Exodus iv. 6; where Moses draws forth his\nHand--not, according to the Persians, \"leprous as Snow,\" but white, as\nour May-blossom in Spring perhaps.  According to them also the Healing\nPower of Jesus resided in his Breath.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 194 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"194"},"sequenceIndex":193},{"id":"rubaiyat-195","text":"(V.) Iram, planted by King Shaddad, and now sunk somewhere in the\nSands of Arabia.  Jamshyd's Seven-ring'd Cup was typical of the 7\nHeavens, 7 Planets, 7 Seas, &c., and was a Divining Cup.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 195 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"195"},"sequenceIndex":194},{"id":"rubaiyat-196","text":"I am not sure if the fourth line refers to the Red Rose looking\nsickly, or to the Yellow Rose that ought to be Red; Red, White, and\nYellow Roses all common in Persia.  I think that Southey in his Common-\nPlace Book, quotes from some Spanish author about the Rose being White\ntill 10 o'clock; \"Rosa Perfecta\" at 2; and \"perfecta incarnada\" at 5.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 196 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"196"},"sequenceIndex":195},{"id":"rubaiyat-197","text":"(X.) Rustum, the \"Hercules\" of Persia, and Zal his Father, whose\nexploits are among the most celebrated in the Shahnama.  Hatim Tai, a\nwell-known type of Oriental Generosity.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 197 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"197"},"sequenceIndex":196},{"id":"rubaiyat-198","text":"(XVIII.) Persepolis: call'd also Takht-i-Jam-shyd--THE THRONE OF\nJAMSHYD, \"King Splendid,\" of the mythical Peshdadian Dynasty, and\nsupposed (according to the Shah-nama) to have been founded and built\nby him.  Others refer it to the Work of the Genie King, Jan Ibn\nJan--who also built the Pyramids--before the time of Adam.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 198 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"198"},"sequenceIndex":197},{"id":"rubaiyat-199","text":"The Palace that to Heav'n his pillars threw,\nAnd Kings the forehead on his threshold drew--\nI saw the solitary Ringdove there,\nAnd \"Coo, coo, coo,\" she cried; and \"Coo, coo, coo.\"","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 199 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"199"},"sequenceIndex":198},{"id":"rubaiyat-200","text":"This Quatrain Mr. Binning found, among several of Hafiz and others,\ninscribed by some stray hand among the ruins of Persepolis.  The\nRingdove's ancient Pehlevi Coo, Coo, Coo, signifies also in Persian\n\"Where? Where?  Where?\"  In Attar's \"Bird-parliament\" she is reproved\nby the Leader of the Birds for sitting still, and for ever harping on\nthat one note of lamentation for her lost Yusuf.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 200 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"200"},"sequenceIndex":199},{"id":"rubaiyat-201","text":"Apropos of Omar's Red Roses in Stanza xix, I am reminded of an old\nEnglish Superstition, that our Anemone Pulsatilla, or purple \"Pasque\nFlower,\" (which grows plentifully about the Fleam Dyke, near\nCambridge,) grows only where Danish Blood has been spilt.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 201 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"201"},"sequenceIndex":200},{"id":"rubaiyat-202","text":"Thus Hafiz, copying Omar in so many ways: \"When thou drinkest Wine\npour a draught on the ground.  Wherefore fear the Sin which brings to\nanother Gain?\"","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 202 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"202"},"sequenceIndex":201},{"id":"rubaiyat-203","text":"(XLIII.) According to one beautiful Oriental Legend, Azrael\naccomplishes his mission by holding to the nostril an Apple from the\nTree of Life.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 203 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"203"},"sequenceIndex":202},{"id":"rubaiyat-204","text":"This, and the two following Stanzas would have been withdrawn, as\nsomewhat de trop, from the Text, but for advice which I least like to\ndisregard.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 204 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"204"},"sequenceIndex":203},{"id":"rubaiyat-205","text":"If we be two, we two are so\nAs stiff twin-compasses are two;\nThy Soul, the fixt foot, makes no show\nTo move, but does if the other do.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 205 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"205"},"sequenceIndex":204},{"id":"rubaiyat-206","text":"And though thine in the centre sit,\nYet when my other far does roam,\nThine leans and hearkens after it,\nAnd rows erect as mine comes home.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 206 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"206"},"sequenceIndex":205},{"id":"rubaiyat-207","text":"Such thou must be to me, who must\nLike the other foot obliquely run;\nThy firmness makes my circle just,\nAnd me to end where I begun.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 207 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"207"},"sequenceIndex":206},{"id":"rubaiyat-208","text":"(LXVIII.) Fanusi khiyal, a Magic-lanthorn still used in India; the\ncylindrical Interior being painted with various Figures, and so\nlightly poised and ventilated as to revolve round the lighted Candle\nwithin.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 208 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"208"},"sequenceIndex":207},{"id":"rubaiyat-209","text":"(LXXXVII.) This Relation of Pot and Potter to Man and his Maker\nfigures far and wide in the Literature of the World, from the time of\nthe Hebrew Prophets to the present; when it may finally take the name\nof \"Pot theism,\" by which Mr. Carlyle ridiculed Sterling's\n\"Pantheism.\"  My Sheikh, whose knowledge flows in from all quarters,\nwrites to me--","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 209 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"209"},"sequenceIndex":208},{"id":"rubaiyat-210","text":"And again--from a very different quarter--\"I had to refer the other\nday to Aristophanes, and came by chance on a curious Speaking-pot\nstory in the Vespae, which I had quite forgotten.","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 210 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"210"},"sequenceIndex":209},{"id":"rubaiyat-211","text":"\"The Pot calls a bystander to be a witness to his bad treatment.  The\nwoman says, 'If, by Proserpine, instead of all this 'testifying'\n(comp. Cuddie and his mother in 'Old Mortality!') you would buy\nyourself a rivet, it would show more sense in you!'  The Scholiast\nexplains echinus as [Greek phrase deleted from etext].\"","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 211 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"211"},"sequenceIndex":210},{"id":"rubaiyat-212","text":"(XC.) At the Close of the Fasting Month, Ramazan (which makes the\nMussulman unhealthy and unamiable), the first Glimpse of the New Moon\n(who rules their division of the Year) is looked for with the utmost\nAnxiety, and hailed with Acclamation.  Then it is that the Porter's\nKnot maybe heard--toward the Cellar.  Omar has elsewhere a pretty\nQuatrain about the same Moon--","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 212 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"212"},"sequenceIndex":211},{"id":"rubaiyat-213","text":"\"Be of Good Cheer--the sullen Month will die,\nAnd a young Moon requite us by and by:\nLook how the Old one meagre, bent, and wan\nWith Age and Fast, is fainting from the Sky!\"","author":"Omar Khayyam","source":"Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam, Stanza 213 (FitzGerald, 5th ed.)","tags":["poetry","persian","philosophy","language:english","collection:rubaiyat"],"groups":{"stanza":"213"},"sequenceIndex":212}]}